\begin{definition}
A morphism \( f : X \to Y \) in the category of Stone spaces is an epimorphism if for any pair of morphisms \( g, h : Y \to Z \), \( g \circ f = h \circ f \) implies \( g = h \).
\end{definition}
<|im_end|>

Step 2: \begin{definition}
A function \( f : X \to Y \) is surjective if for every \( y \in Y \), there exists \( x \in X \) such that \( f(x) = y \).
\end{definition}<|im_end|>

Step 6: \begin{proof}
To verify that \( p \) is an epimorphism, consider any pair of continuous functions \( g, h : S \to Z \) where \( Z \) is another Stone space. If \( g \circ p = h \circ p \), then for any \( (s, t) \in S \times [0,1] \), we have \( g(s) = h(s) \). Since \( g \) and \( h \) are continuous and \( S \) is discrete, \( g \) and \( h \) must agree on all points of \( S \), implying \( g = h \). Thus, \( p \) is an epimorphism.
\end{proof}<|im_end|>
